## Data set

The following data set comprises the details and results for the past five Winter Olympics in the Women's figure skating discipline starting from 2006. The choice of year is for consistency, as in 2006 the International Skating Union (ISU) introduced a new scoring system. With this data set I aim to visualize the general curve of scores in the women's discipline and see if there's been a big jump since harder jumps have become the norm.

***Olympic Results - Women's Figure Skating***

Now let's take a look at the average Olympic scores over the years.

```{r, eval=TRUE, echo=FALSE}


library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)


olympic_results <- read.csv("olympic_results_women.csv")

fs_results <- olympic_results %>%
  filter(discipline_title == "Figure skating" &
         grepl("women", event_title, ignore.case = TRUE)) %>%
  select(year, value_unit)

average_fs_scores <- fs_results %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(avg_fs_score = mean(value_unit, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(average_fs_scores, aes(x = year, y = avg_fs_score)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
  labs(
    x = "Year/Event",
    y = "Average Free Skate Score",
    title = "Average Free Skate Scores at the Olympics Over Time"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

```

**World's Championship's Scores**

The following database contains the results of the top 10 skaters at the World figure skating championships of the past 10 years in the women's discipline. The focus being on the last 10 years is to analyze if there has been a noticeable difference between among technical and performance scores since the introduction of higher value elements such as quads.

```{r, eval=TRUE, echo=FALSE}
library(tidyverse)
library(knitr)

worlds_results <- read.csv("FS World scores women.csv")

kable(worlds_results)
```

Now let's look a the general curve of the scores over the last ten years.

*\*Must be noted that the 2020 World championships were cancelled due to the pandemic.*

```{r, eval=TRUE, echo=FALSE}

library(dplyr)

worlds_results <- read.csv("FS World scores women.csv")

mean_scores_by_year <- worlds_results %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_sp_tes = mean(SP_TES, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_sp_tes = mean(FS_TES, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

mean_pcs_by_year <- worlds_results %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise (
    mean_fs_pcs = mean(FS_PCS, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_sp_pcs = mean(SP_PCS, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

library(ggplot2)

mean_scores_by_year <- worlds_results %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_sp_tes = mean(SP_TES, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_fs_tes = mean(FS_TES, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_sp_pcs = mean(SP_PCS, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_fs_pcs = mean(FS_PCS, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

mean_scores_long <- mean_scores_by_year %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("mean_"),
               names_to = "score_type",
               values_to = "mean_score")

ggplot(mean_scores_long, aes(x = Year, y = mean_score, color = score_type)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Mean Score",
       title = "Mean Scores Over Years") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("mean_sp_tes" = "blue", "mean_fs_tes" = "green",
                                 "mean_sp_pcs" = "red", "mean_fs_pcs" = "orange"),
                     labels = c("Mean SP TES", "Mean FS TES", "Mean SP PCS", "Mean FS PCS")) +
  theme_minimal()

```

In this line plot, we can notice that the technical scores fluctuate more than the performance scores do. As can be noted there was a spike in technical score between 2017 to 2020. This can be attributed to Russian skaters dominating the podium during those years, more specifically Evgenia Medvedeva, who was known for her triple-triple-triple jump combination. After that, there was a drop in the scores and it has been declining ever since. 

It is interesting to note that although quadruple jumps have been in the rise among the women's discipline, the technical scores have not seen a higher attribution. For instance in 2022 while the quad revolution was at its peak, the technical and performance scores remained at about the same average.

It must be noted that Russian athletes have been banned from competing at international competitions due to sanctions related to doping and war conflicts. Hence why, quadruple jumps after the 2022 Olympics are not as common among women.

### Relationship between Technical and Performance score

From what we've seen, the scores remain fairly consistent and whenever there is a huge spike, there are many factors that influence it. Now let's visualize the correlation between performance and technical scores in order to identify skaters that excel on both elements and take into consideration how the difficulty of their programs impacted their scores.


```{r, eval=TRUE, echo=FALSE}
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

worlds_results <- read.csv("FS World scores women.csv")

mean_pcs_scores <- worlds_results %>%
  group_by(Skater_Lastname) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_pcs_FS = mean(FS_PCS, na.rm = TRUE), 
    mean_pcs_SP = mean(SP_PCS, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

mean_tes_scores <- worlds_results %>%
  group_by(Skater_Lastname) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_tes_FS = mean(FS_TES, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_tes_SP = mean(SP_TES, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

mean_scores <- merge(mean_pcs_scores, mean_tes_scores, by = "Skater_Lastname")

ggplot(mean_scores, aes(x = mean_tes_FS, y = mean_pcs_FS, label = Skater_Lastname)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_text(size = 3, hjust = -0.2, vjust = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "Mean Technical Score (TES) - Free Skate",
       y = "Mean Performance Score (PCS) - Free Skate",
       title = "Correlation Between Technical and Performance Scores (Free Skate)") +
  theme_minimal()
```
As can be seen in this graph, most skaters tend to have consistent difference between their performance scores and their technical scores. Skaters such as Trusova have a huge gap with a high technical score but lower performance score. It must be noted she's among the few female skaters that can perform quadruple jumps. In her case, it can be assumed that posing a higher focus on jumps does have a negative effect on the performance components.

## Conclusion

There hasn't been a notable difference among the technical scores of figure skaters. It remains pretty consistent and since the ban of Russian competitive skaters from international competitions, the gap has become less big among the women's discipline. 
 


